Use of AI In Astronaut Therapeutic Testing

Historically, drug discovery has been an extremely slow, expensive, and high-risk process. 
Developing even a single therapeutic often requires years of receptor identification, laboratory testing, large clinical studies, and the evaluation of thousands of molecular candidates before identifying one that is both effective and safe.
As previously mentioned, the complex environments in long-term spaceflight make this challenge even greater due to the unique physiological changes that cannot be traditionally accounted for.

Very recent advances in artificial intelligence and machine learning have significantly accelerated this process. 
Many scientists who study both the arts of biochemistry and computer science have integrated large databases of existing proteins and small molecules into contemporary algorithms that can accelerate the drug discovery process by years.

In research papers and research labs, a common workflow has been identified starting with identifying a G Protein-Coupled Receptor responsible for the effects to mitigate, using AI to generate a peptide backbone to inhibit the receptor, using AI to generate an amino acid sequence that will fold into that peptide backbone, then using AI to verify that the amino acid sequence will actually fold into that structure.
Below is the workflow that our labs at the University of Houston adopt, which we plan to utilize to target the inhibition of bone density loss, muscle atrophy, and neurodegeneration.

